   <text>
      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1044">
               <p>Holland, a painter of <placeName>Basinghall Street, London</placeName>, was a
                  devout member of the Church of <placeName>England</placeName> who in <date
                     when="1738">1738</date> introduced the Wesley brothers to Luther&apos;s
                  commentaries on Galatians and Romans. He was a founding member of the Fetter Lane
                  society. When the Wesley brothers withdrew in <date when="1740">1740</date>,
                  Holland and his wife <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0566.xml"/>Elizabeth (née
                     Delamotte</persName>, a sister of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0565.xml"
                     />Charles</persName> and <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0569.xml"
                     />William</persName>) remained in this now solidly Moravian society. Indeed,
                  Holland became one of the leading officers and preachers of the Moravians,
                  succeeding <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2102.xml"/>Richard Viney</persName>
                  in charge of their settlement at <placeName>Fulneck, Yorkshire</placeName>. In
                  late <date when="1747">1747</date> he left the Moravians (though his wife
                  remained), returned to the Church of <placeName>England</placeName>, and sought to
                  renew friendship with <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>
                  and <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName>. See <hi
                     rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 567–68; and <hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi>.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
